This is the first post on AutoTechify, so let me start with the basics: who I
am, why this site exists, and who I'm building it for.

## Who I am

I'm Swarim Abdussamad. I work at an FMCG company in Qatar — mainly food
products, with some construction materials and automobile parts on the side.
I've been here about five months, and I'm a developer sitting inside a real,
established business.

That last part matters. In five months I've seen how much actually happens
behind the scenes of a company like this — a huge amount of process, every
single day. And a lot of it still runs on old, slow, manual methods that are
time-consuming and not always accurate. Almost every one of those processes is
something a developer can improve, automate, and make reliable.

## Why this blog

The more I saw, the more obvious it became: this isn't unique to my company.
Every business owner, entrepreneur, and team is dealing with the same kind of
work. So why keep what I learn to myself?

AutoTechify is where I share the actual tools and automations I use — the
real ones running in production, not theory. The goal is simple: help other
business owners save time and money, and give developers something concrete to
reference when they want to automate inside their own companies.

No SEO padding. If I haven't built it or lived it, I won't write about it.

## A real example: cutting ERP costs with daily automation

Most companies today run on an ERP. We do too — and with 10+ branches, a large
volume of data piles up and gets structured in the system every single day.

The ERP is built by a service provider, and we buy it. The problem is the one
every owner knows: even for a small change, they ask for more money. I think
about this the way a business owner would — always trying to cut expense, while
still demanding a system that's actually perfect for us.

So as a developer, I just built around it. Every day an automation logs into
the ERP with our credentials, downloads the MIS report, and feeds it into a
small internal tool I built — an "Office Manager." It then presents the numbers
the way a business owner actually wants to see them.

- A **daily cron job** pulls and refreshes the latest figures
- A **weekly cron job** builds out the bigger picture: the exact organization
  tree, MTD sales analysis and distribution, and year-over-year comparisons

Yes, the ERP already has a dashboard. But this is more advanced, and — more
importantly — I can adjust it ourselves whenever we need to, instead of paying
and waiting for the provider. For tracking salesmen and reading the real state
of the company, this kind of view is genuinely useful to an owner.

That's the spirit of everything here: see a slow or expensive process, and
replace it with something automated, accurate, and ours.

## Coming soon: a free Meta CRM

Almost every business runs on a CRM or BSP of some kind. As a developer, that's
